definition.value: An amide fungicide whose structure contains a sulfonamide moiety.

A water soluble mixture of different dyes extracted from various species of lichens particularly Variolaria, Lecanora and Rocella. Consists chiefly of azolitmin and erythrolitmin combined with alkalis. Used as an acid-base indicator pH 4.5 red, 8.3 blue.

The parent member of the class of flexirubins obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 17-(4-hydroxy-3-methylphenyl)heptadeca-2,4,6,8,10,12,14,16-octaenoic acid with one of the phenolic hydroxy groups of 2-dodecyl-5-methyl resorcinol.

Flexirubins are a unique type of pigment produced by various bacteria species characterised by a common structure comprising  non-isoprenoid omega-substituted polyene carboxylic acids esterified with 2,5-dialkylated resorcinols.
An organic aromatic compound that has been used as a fungicide.
Any organic aromatic compound containing two phenyl (or substituted phenyl) groups attached to a single carbon or heteroatom and which has been used as a fungicide.

A mixture of polysaccharides made up from alternating D-galactose and 3,6-anhydro-alpha-L-galactopyranose residues joined by beta-(1->3)-linkages. Some of the galactosyl units may be sulfated. Agaropectin provides the viscous properties of agar.
An aminoglycoside antibiotic that is part of an antimicrobial complex consisting of factors 1,2,3,5 from a soil isolate named Streptomyces hofunensis.
A macrolide antibiotic with activity against Neisseria gonorrhoeae, Chlamydia trachomatis, Ureaplasma urealyticum and Mycoplasma hominis.
Any triazole antifungal agent that has been used as a fungicide.
Any antibiotic antifungal agent used to treat fungal infections in humans or animals.
Any antibiotic antifungal agent that has been used as a fungicide.
A hexosamine phosphate that is fructosamine carrying a monophosphate group at position 3. The deglycation product of fructosamine
A hexosamine phosphate that is any fructosamine carrying a monophosphate group at position 3. The deglycation product of psicosamine.
A magnesium salt composed of Mg(2+) and ADP(2-) ions in a 1:1 ratio. Magnesium-ADP is a potassium channel activator.
A hydrazone resulting from the formal condensation of an aldehyde or ketone with the non-acylated nitrogen of semicarbazide or its substituted derivatives.
An organonitrogen heterocyclic antibiotic containing a quinolone (or quinolone-like) moiety and which have a fluorine atom attached to the central ring system.
A class of sulfonamides whose members generally have bacteriostatic antibiotic properties.
A member of the class of furans in which the furan ring is substituted by a nitro group and which also has significant antibiotic properties.
A phosphonic ester obtained by the esterification of both the hydroxy groups of butylphosphonic acid with ethanol and 2-phenylethanol respectively.
A glucosylglycerol phosphate consisting of sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having an alpha-D-glucosyl residue attached at position 2.

An organosulfonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the sulfo and carboxy groups of 5-[(3-carboxy-5-methyl-4-oxocyclohexa-2,5-dien-1-ylidene)(2-sulfophenyl)methyl]-2-hydroxy-3-methylbenzoic acid.

A member of the class of benzoic acids that is 2-hydroxy-3-methyl-5-[(2-sulfophenyl)methyl]benzoic acid in which both of the benzylic hydrogens are replaced by a 3-carboxy-5-methyl-4-oxocyclohexa-2,5-dien-1-ylidene group. The trisodium salt is the biological stain 'chromoxane cyanin R'.

A member of the class of quinomethanes that is 3-methylidene-6-oxocyclohexa-1,4-diene-1-carboxylic acid in which the methylidene hydrogens are replaced by 4-carboxy-3-hydroxyphenyl groups. The trisodium salt is the biological stain 'chrome violet CG' while the triammonium salt is 'aluminon'.

An ammonium salt that is the ammonium salt of 3,3'-[(3-carboxy-4-oxocyclohexa-2,5-dien-1-ylidene)methylene]bis(6-hydroxybenzoic acid). A dye commonly used to detect the presence of the aluminium ion in an aqueous solution.
A cyclodepsipeptide antibiotic that is isolated from Streptomyces sp. SNA15896 and also exhibits antitumour activity.
A cyclodepsipeptide antibiotic that is isolated from Streptomyces sp. SNA15896 and also exhibits antitumour activity.
A cyclodepsipeptide antibiotic that is isolated from Streptomyces sp. SNA15896 and also exhibits antitumour activity.
A disaccharide formed by hexopyranoside and hex-2-ulofuranose units joined by an acetal oxygen bridge from hemiacetal of hexopyranoside to the hemiketal of the hex-2-ulofuranose.
A long-chain alkane consisting of an unbranched chain of 34 carbon atoms.
A hydroxyether that is propan-1-ol substituted by an ethoxy group at position 3.
A flavin mononucleotide obtained by prenylation of the N-10 position of FMNH2 followed by cyclisation. An essential cofactor for the decarboxylase enzymes UbiD and Fdc1.

Any organooxygen compound whose structure is related to compactin (mevastatin) and which may be used as an anticholesteremic drug due its EC 1.1.1.34/EC 1.1.1.88 (hydroxymethylglutaryl-CoA reductase) inhibitory properties.

Any statin that occurs in nature. The class includes compactin (also known as mevastatin), isolated from a fermentation broth of Penicillium citrinum, and lovastatin, isolated from Aspergillus terreus.
A statin that is derived from a naturally occurring statin by partial chemical synthesis.
Any fatty acid ester where the carboxylic acid component is hexanoic (also known as caproic) acid.
Any fatty acid ester in which the carboxylic acid component is octanoic acid (caprylic acid).
A fatty acid ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of decanoic acid (capric acid) with the hydroxy group of an alcohol or phenol.
Any fatty acid ester in which the carboxylic acid component is lauric acid.
A four-component mixture of chemically related dyes comprising pararosanilin, rosanilin, magenta II and new fuchsin in varying amounts

A hydrochloride that is the monohydrochloride of 4-[(4-aminophenyl)(4-iminocyclohexa-2,5-dien-1-ylidene)methyl]-2-methylaniline. One of the major constituents of Basic fuchsin, together with pararosanilin, magenta II and new fuchsin.
An iminium ion obtained by protonation of the imino group of rosanilin free base.
A fatty acid ester obtained by condensation of the carboxy group of tetradecanoic acid (also known as myristic acid) with a hydroxy group of an alcohol or phenol.
A flavin mononucleotide resulting from the formal dehydrogenation of prenyl-FMNH2. It is an essential cofactor for the decarboxylase enzymes UbiD (Fdc1).
A bile acid salt that is the sodium salt of glycochenodeoxycholic acid.
A bile acid salt that is the sodium salt of glycodeoxycholic acid.
An L-alpha-amino acid that is L-valine in which all five carbons are (13)C isotopes while the nitrogen is the (15)N isotope.
A glucitol that is D-glucitol in which the carbon at position 1 is the (13)C isotope.
Riboflavin in which the double bond between positions 4a and 5 has been reduced to a single bond.

An alpha,omega-dicarboxylic acid that is suberic acid which oxo groups replace the hydrogens at positions 3 and 5. It is an abnormal metabolite of the tyrosine metabolic pathway and a marker for type 1 tyrosinaemia.
